{{Infobox person | name = Grigory Dzhanshiyev | image = Grigory Avetovich Dzhanshiyev.jpg | imagesize = 180px | caption = | birthname = Григорий Аветович Джаншиев | birth_date = {{Birth date|1851|5|29}} | birth_place = [[Tiflis]], [[Russian Empire]] (modern [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]) | death_date = {{Death date and age|1900|7|30|1851|5|29}} | death_place = Saint Petersburg, Russian Empire | occupation = lawyer, writer, publicist, historian | years_active = | spouse = | website = | awards = }}
'''Grigory Avetovich Dzhanshiyev''' ({{lang-hy|Գրիգոր Ավետի Ջանշյան}}; {{lang-ru|Григорий Аветович Джаншиев}}, 29 May 1851, [[Tiflis]], [[Russian Empire]], now [[Georgia (republic)|Georgia]], — 30 July 1900, [[Moscow]], Russian Empire) was Russian [[lawyer]], [[publicist]] and [[historian]] of [[Armenians|Armenian]] descent. A [[Moscow University]] alumnus, Dzhanshiyev authored 25 books, the best-known of which, ''On the Times of the Great Reform'' (Из эпохи великих реформ, 1892), was re-issued several times in his lifetime and is considered one of the best treatises on [[Alexander II of Russia|Alexander II]]'s reforms in law and [[jurisdiction]]. Dzhanshiyev was also one of the authors of the [[Brockhaus and Efron Encyclopedic Dictionary]].<ref>Dzhanshiyev at the Great Soviet Encyclopedia // Джаншиев Григорий Аветович. Большая советская энциклопедия. — М.: Советская энциклопедия, 1969—1978.</ref><ref>[http://www.rulex.ru/01050388.htm Джаншиев Григорий Аветович] at the Russian Biographical Dictionary</ref>
